    "response_text": "An atom and a molecule are two fundamental concepts in chemistry that are often confused with each other, but they have distinct differences.\n\n**Atom:**\nAn atom is the smallest unit of a chemical element that retains the properties of that element. It consists of three main parts:\n\n1. **Protons**: Positively charged particles found in the nucleus (center) of the atom.\n2. **Neutrons**: Particles with no charge found in the nucleus, which contribute to the atom's mass.\n3. **Electrons**: Negatively charged particles that orbit around the nucleus.\n\nAtoms are the building blocks of matter, and they can be combined to form molecules.\n\n**Molecule:**\nA molecule is a group of two or more atoms that are chemically bonded together. Molecules can be composed of atoms of the same element (such as oxygen gas, O2) or different elements (such as water, H2O). The atoms in a molecule are held together by chemical bonds,",
